'''Paul Clarke''' (born 11 October 1956) is a Scottish former professional [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] as a [[Defender (association football)|centre-back]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player1/paulclarke.html|title=Profile|accessdate=22 May 2014|publisher=Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Player's Transfer Database}}</ref>

==Career==
Clarke spent some time in the youth team ''Kilmarnock Star'' alongside future team-mate at senior level, [[Stuart McLean (footballer)|Stuart McLean]],<ref name= interview>{{cite web|url=http://www.killiefc.com/en/paul-clarke_50936/|title=Interview with Paul Clarke|author=Donny Muir|publisher=KillieFC.com|date=2001|accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> and had a loan spell in the [[Scottish Junior Football Association|Junior leagues]] with local [[Ardrossan Winton Rovers F.C.|Ardrossan Winton Rovers]] after signing provisionally with Kilmarnock.

His debut for ''Killie'' was versus [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] at [[Rugby Park]] in the [[Scottish League Cup]] on 9 August 1975,<ref name= interview/> he scored Kilmarnock's first goal in the [[Scottish Football League Premier Division|Premier Division format]] on 4 September 1976 at home to [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]],<ref name= interview/> and his final game was also at home versus [[Ayrshire derby]] rivals [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] in a league match on 3 May 1986.<ref name=fsprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/kilmarnock/player.php?playerid=7518|title=Kilmarnock player Paul Clarke|website=Fitbastats|accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>

He left the club and retired from professional football at the age of 29 to join [[Strathclyde Police]] before reaching their upper recruitment age limit;<ref name= interview/> despite ending his career early, he is ranked 11th on Kilmarnock's all-time appearance list, having played in 436 matches across 11 seasons in the three major competitions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/kilmarnock/player_records_overall.php|title=Kilmarnock FC player records|publisher=fitbastats.com|accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>

Clarke's two [[Scottish League XI]] caps were versus Italy B in 1978 and League of Ireland in 1980.<ref>{{cite book |last=Cairns |first=Richard |date=2011 |title=Killie 'Til I Die |url= |location= |publisher=Fasprint Services (Irvine) Ltd |page= |isbn=978-0-9541653-1-4|author-link= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/SFL/players/paulclarke.html|title=Scottish League XI Paul Clarke|publisher=London Hearts|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref>

He later became involved in coaching the youth teams at Kilmarnock.<ref name= interview/>

==Personal life==
Paul is the older brother of the current Scotland national football team manager and former [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] defender, [[Steve Clarke]].<ref name= interview/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/amp/football/41640522 |title=Kilmarnock: Steve Clarke believes his managerial record deserves more respect |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=16 October 2017 |accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> The siblings played against each other during the [[1982–83 in Scottish football|1982–83 season]] when Steve was with [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]; on 4 December 1982, Paul scored both Kilmarnock goals in a 2-2 draw between the sides at Rugby Park.<ref name= interview/><ref name=fsprofile/>

